Until the 1970s, watching dump-diving grizzlies was a popular attraction at Yellowstone.
In the 1960s, the Yellowstone bears were hurt by habitat loss.
The Natural Resources Defense Council, the Sierra Club and other groups say that too many threats still exist for the bears.
"It's probably one of the most studied mammals in the world," said Chuck Schwartz, head of the Interagency Grizzly Bear Study Team, in Bozeman, Mont., which has primary responsibility for studying the Yellowstone bear.
